{
  "text": "When a large pulse ( corresponding to more than 10 PEs) enters the PMT, a smaller after-pulse can be created that may survive the aforementioned large-PE veto. However, since these after-pulses are generated within roughly 10 microseconds, it will stay within the deadtime of the readout board (considered in Ref. [CITATION_1] ) triggered by the large pulse and thus not being recorded.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "119252127"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "119252127": {
      "title": "A Letter of Intent to Install a milli-charged Particle Detector at LHC P5",
      "abstract": "In this LOI we propose a dedicated experiment that would detect \"milli-charged\" particles produced by pp collisions at LHC Point 5. The experiment would be installed during LS2 in the vestigial drainage gallery above UXC and would not interfere with CMS operations. With 300 fb$^{-1}$ of integrated luminosity, sensitivity to a particle with charge $\\mathcal{O}(10^{-3})~e$ can be achieved for masses of $\\mathcal{O}(1)$ GeV, and charge $\\mathcal{O}(10^{-2})~e$ for masses of $\\mathcal{O}(10)$ GeV, greatly extending the parameter space explored for particles with small charge and masses above 100 MeV."
    }
  }
}